Triggers — and the time-based versus data-driven decision the exam loves.

A trigger is simply what fires a job run. There are five options, but the first three matter most.

Scheduled, or cron — the time-based trigger — runs at a specific quartz-cron time. Zero-zero-two-star-star-question-mark means every day at two a-m U-T-C. It's best when your source lands on a predictable cadence.

File arrival runs when new files land in a path. Lakeflow Jobs polls that path, and fires the job when it sees new files. Best when the landing time is irregular.

Table update runs when a Delta table gets a new commit. Best when your dependency is table state — for instance, rebuild gold whenever silver changes.

Then two more: continuous, which runs forever and is only for a declarative pipeline in continuous mode; and manual, which has no trigger at all — a human or an A-P-I call starts it, which is handy for ad-hoc backfills.

Now, the exam frames almost every trigger question as one tradeoff: time-based versus data-driven. Choose time-based, cron, when the data lands predictably, when you want a stable execution window for S-L-As and cost forecasting, and when "fresh as of midnight" is good enough. Choose data-driven — file arrival or table update — when landing time is variable, when you want to minimise latency and run as soon as data is available, and when empty polled runs would be wasteful.

And here's the classic scenario. A partner drops a file at an unpredictable time each night, and the team wants to ingest as soon as it lands, without running an empty job every hour. The answer is the file-arrival trigger. Cron is the deliberate distractor — it either misses the file or wastes compute polling for it.
